# Debugging Failing Tests

When a test fails:

1. **Investigate the implementation first.** Reproduce the failure, read the code under test, and determine whether the bug is in the production/source logic (wrong behavior, missing edge case, accessibility/semantics bug, etc.).
2. **Fix the real issue** in the production code when you find one.
3. **Only then** consider changing the test — e.g. if the test was asserting on the wrong element, had wrong expectations, or the API/contract legitimately changed.

**Do not** change or relax the test solely to make it pass without understanding and fixing the underlying cause. If you only change the test, you may be hiding a real bug.
